George (February 10, 1910 - July 1974) and Leslie York  (August 23, 1917 - February 21, 1984), known professionally as The York Brothers, were an American country music duo, popular from the late 1930s through the 1950s, known for their close harmony singing.

Although originally from Kentucky, they are often associated with the city of Detroit, where they were based for several years, and which they paid tribute to in songs such as "Hamtramck Mama", "Detroit Hula Girl", and "Motor City Boogie".
Meanwhile, Leslie (who was seven years younger than George) finished 9th grade, and won a talent contest in Lexington, Kentucky.
Detroit's auto industry in the late 1930s employed thousands of Southerners.
In 1939 they recorded their first single, "Hamtramck Mama," which became a hit on the Detroit-based Universal label – selling some 300,000 copies in the Detroit area alone.
More successful singles followed, and in 1941 the brothers signed with Decca Records.
By the start of 1944, however, both brothers were in the Navy, with George serving in the Pacific and Leslie in Europe.
In 1946, with the war over, the brothers reunited and moved to Nashville, Tennessee.
They survived the 1948 AFM recording ban with steady live work, including a six-week stint with the Louisiana Hayride, and remained with the Opry until 1950, when they returned to Detroit.
